@@cKNIGHT@@W

@@cHistory@@W
  Knights trace their lineage to the Iron Reformation, when the warlords of
  the eastern campaigns realized that warrior strength alone could not hold a
  siege line. The first Knights were heavy infantry officers trained under the
  Compact of the Seven Chains -- an agreement between warring clans that
  established mutual rules of engagement. Bound by oath to their standard,
  they developed a fighting doctrine built around body mechanics, controlled
  aggression, and formation superiority. Over generations the tradition
  formalized into academies where recruits underwent years of weapon drill
  before taking the field. Their creed: break the line, hold the ground,
  leave no fallen comrade behind.

Knights are disciplined line-breakers: armored tacticians who seize momentum
through relentless body-strike chains and weapon control.

